"This is all the WAU, right? It's looking for anything, anything alive." Always thought Simon should have somehow destroyed the brain of the last living human. There's a bunch of WAU structure gel growths in her room already. What's to stop them from growing into her and reanimating her like those dudes on the bunks downstairs?
;
The dude that's got all the tentacles growing into him holding the picture of his kid is still semi-conscious too. It'd be a real horrorshow if the last living human went out thinking she could die in peace only to get pulled back in as another post-human monstrosity.

​ @assistantmagus5213  "because it was capturing scans of their brains when they used the pilot seats" Those are the Mockingbirds, like Catherine Mk3. I'm talking about the post-humans, the creatures formed from human bodies who are embedded in walls or independently active like discoball-head.
;
"Once you're dead your consciousness stops and you cease existing, the WAU cant bring you back" I'm not so sure that's true. The dude with the tentacles in him on the bed twitches and mumbles the name of his kid. So he still has some degree of motor function and memory. That seems more like he died but then the WAU reanimated him with brain damage.
;
Then there's the case of Johan Ross who died and was rebuilt by the WAU as a post-human but still retains full consciousness and will in his original body.

​ @Th3Sh1n1gam1  "so in the end... did humanity end because what we recognize as humans no longer exist? or did humanity actually overcome extinction if the Wau continued to exist and create its version of humanity." Personally I'd say humanity has ended as even the most sapient of the WAU's bunch, the Mockingbirds, generally don't regard each other as human. They regard each other as robots and even Catherine and Simon do so.
;
If there's to be a humanity then I think a basic requirement would be for most members of the species to recognize other members of the species.

​ @Ζήνων-ζ1ι  In the room Simon Mk 3's trapped in at the end of the game? He was the only one.
;
Your point doesn't make any sense given how badly off all the post-humans are. A third of them are immobile lumps stuck in a wall, another third are howling lunatics, and another third aren't even conscious. Instead of generalizing it to "a lot of NPCs" can you name one of the NPCs encountered during the course of the game was even remotely capable of building a society?
;
"Somehow." How? Be specific. How is Carl who's legless and attached to a conveyer line or the DUNBAT which is raging out and screaming how he can't take it! he can't take it! gonna form any kind of meaningful structure or hierarchy?

​ @Ζήνων-ζ1ι  "But looking at it realistically, these "post humans" wouldn't even be in this state to begin with. Even if initially they were to fall into that, they would eventually reject it." But that doesn't make any sense. Everything you're talking about regarding the human spirit is a metaphysical quality, but the post-humans have physical limitations. How does Carl 'reject' being fused to an assembly line?
;
If it were a situation where PATHOS was just left alone, they would probably have been fine. They had an organizational structure which could have evolved into a government, they had a large enough population to maintain genetic diversity, they had a stable geothermal power source, could maintain their habitat via structure gel, and the undersea ecosystems were still running, so they had fish to eat. In that situation they could have gone on and produced a society and all the things you talk about, and eventually their descendants would have repopulated the surface.
;
But the problem is they weren't left alone, they had to contend with the WAU. The WAU is a physical entity that exists and the problems it causes are physical. It's not just a matter of rejecting existential despair or something, it's a matter of 'oh hey I'm a techno-zombie and I have no legs'

 @Fraggr92  I think the coin flip idea is philosophically solid from the right perspective. The "chance" comes not from a possibility of the original somehow becoming the copy on the ARK, but from the somewhat abstract question of "Why am I me?". The Simon on the Ark is "lucky" to be the one of the two experiencing the Ark. It just gets weird because both results of the coin flip occur, and the only thing differentiating the two Simons is their respective result.

But I think its validity is dependent upon one's feelings about the question "Is a perfect copy of you still you?". If you somehow learned that every time you went to sleep and woke up that the consciousness that woke up was a copy of the one that went to sleep, would you still carry on as normal or lament the fact that you are going to die at the end of the day? 

If a person who feels that the copy is a continuation of the original rather than being a totally separate entity were in Simon's situation and wanted to get onto the ARK, the coin flip model makes sense. Even if they're only self-interested and care nothing for the other copy post-divergence, they would still be motivated to reach the ARK because, from their perspective, there's a 50% chance that they'll be satisfied with the result.

 @jackreid2664  Thinking of it as a coin toss is a way to avoid thinking that you left behind the other you. But in the case of Simon it is a failure of his understanding.

The way I see it is like a "brain mitosis" of sorts. You make a copy and now there's a branching continuation, the copy shares your experiences but is now a different person.
Too bad the WAU was dumb, if it copied Catherine around it could've made more stable machines that could actually do something other than spread like a cancer and "fix" things..

@LD TV i also think the guy missed the point of the game, the ark was never meant to be the salvation of humanity, it was the last struggle of what remained of humanity, a pet project that was not going to last forever but in the eyes of what remained of humanity on the bottom of the sea, it was something worth doing.

from my understanding, the WAU was doing whatever it could to keep humans alive, no matter how twisted that may look in our eyes.

also from my understanding the surface of the earth got wiped out by the comet.

